It seems as though the world is on the fast lane toward cleaning the car industry from polluting emissions. Everyone is rushing to create clean cars, whether battery or hydrogen powered engines, and bask in their cleanness.
But the green alibi hides behind it a dirty truth: Zero emission does not mean zero pollution. Mining rare Earth materials required for zero-emissions engines, building charging stations, and the complex logistics surrounding the ‚Äúclean‚Äù industries will take a heavy toll on Earth. In the end, the only ones who will gain from the ‚Äúclean revolution‚Äù are the tycoons who are selling it to us, and the government officials who placate them for their own reasons.
Where is Greta Thunberg these days? Like the rest of the pawns in the battle for wealth and power, the ‚Äúclimate knights‚Äù have sent her back to oblivion once they finished using her. It is all power games among giant corporations, but the environment and the climate are no one‚Äôs concern.
Even if we switch to wind energy or ocean-wave energy, I don‚Äôt believe that we will gain much. We will have to pay for it elsewhere.
For this reason, I think that the crux of the problem is not emissions, but our behavior toward nature and toward our fellow human beings. Here is where we can produce positive and lasting results. If we could communicate with one another positively, we could stop the madness of excessive development that manufactures unnecessary and harmful products.
If we could slow down a bit, we wouldn‚Äôt need to burn so much fuel in order to defeat competitors in a race for wealth that makes no one happy. Only if we realize that our happiness depends on the quality of our relationships, and not on the padding of our bank accounts, we will be able to pause a little, think, and rebuild our civilization in a way that contributes to nature, to humanity, and to each of us.

My son had to be inoculated for COVID-19 for his job working with troubled teenagers. He had a severe reaction and only recovered after two trips to the Emergency room and a short stay in the hospital. Once he was able to return to work, his employer cut his work hours to the point that he had to seek employment elsewhere.
I gave a lot of thought to what he went through. I thought about a good friend who was a diabetic that had a fatal reaction to the inoculation. I considered several friends who had died from COVID-19 and others who had various reactions to the inoculations. I discussed my concerns with my doctor who I have and will continue to rely upon, and she advised me that due to my age and health issues the advantages of receiving the inoculations far outweigh the disadvantages. I considered my Son and his family, and other relatives and friends that I enjoy visiting with and decided to get the inoculations. I had no reaction to the first shot but did have to the second. Luckily the reactions were not near as severe as my son had. I don't regret my decision to receive the inoculations but I also would not begin to judge anyone else if they decided not to be inoculated. At this point, I do not believe that it should be mandatory for everyone to get the shots, and that it should remain elective, like flu shots. My opinion may change as time passes, but at this time I feel that many that would possibly have decided to receive the inoculations will resist a mandate requiring them to comply.
